  <h2 id="what-is-used-oil">What is Used Oil?</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 40 Gs with separation down to 0.5 microns. Used oil is any petroleum-based or synthetic lubricant that has been contaminated through normal use. Engine oils, hydraulic fluids, gear oils, transformer oils, and metalworking fluids all become "used oil" once they pick up contaminants such as dirt, metal shavings, water, and combustion byproducts.
  </p>

  <p>
    The United States generates over <strong>2 billion gallons</strong> of used oil annually. Improper disposal of this volume poses a significant environmental threat. Centrifugal separation is the most efficient industrial method for reclaiming used oil into a valuable commodity.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Used vs Waste Oil ── -->
  <h2 id="used-vs-waste-oil">Used Oil vs. Waste Oil</h2>

  <p>
    Although the terms are sometimes used interchangeably, used oil and waste oil have distinct definitions that affect handling, regulation, and end-use options.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Used Oil:</strong> Petroleum-based or synthetic oil that has been contaminated through use. It retains its original mineral or synthetic base and can typically be re-refined or reclaimed for further use.</li>
    <li><strong>Waste Oil:</strong> Oil that includes organic-origin contaminants (vegetable oils, animal fats) or has been mixed with solvents, fuels, or other non-petroleum substances. Waste oil often requires different handling and disposal methods due to its mixed composition.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The distinction is important because used oil is a far better candidate for reclamation via centrifugation. Its mineral or synthetic base remains stable, and contaminants can be mechanically separated without altering the base stock.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Reclaiming Used Oil ── -->
  <h2 id="reclaiming-used-oil">Reclaiming Used Oil</h2>

  <p>
    Reclaiming used oil serves both environmental and economic goals. Every gallon of used oil that is properly processed eliminates the pollution risk of improper disposal and creates a valuable product.
  </p>

  <h3>End-Use Applications for Reclaimed Oil</h3>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Re-refined Lubricant Base Stock:</strong> Used oil can be processed back into high-quality base oil suitable for blending into new lubricants.</li>
    <li><strong>Industrial Heating Fuel:</strong> Cleaned used oil meets specifications for use in approved industrial burners and boilers.</li>
    <li><strong>Black Diesel:</strong> Centrifuge-processed used oil can be refined into <a href="/black-diesel-centrifuge/">black diesel fuel</a> for off-road equipment and generators.</li>
    <li><strong>Pollution Reduction:</strong> Proper reclamation prevents soil and groundwater contamination from dumped or leaked used oil.</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    A single gallon of improperly disposed used oil can contaminate one million gallons of fresh water. Centrifugal reclamation is the most efficient path from contaminated oil to usable product.
  </blockquote>

  <!-- ── Methods of Recovery ── -->
  <h2 id="methods-of-recovery">Methods of Used Oil Recovery</h2>

  <h3>Conventional Methods: Heating, Settling & Filtration</h3>

  <p>
    Traditional used oil recovery relies on heating the oil to reduce viscosity, allowing contaminants to settle by gravity, then filtering the supernatant through bag or cartridge filters. This approach has significant limitations:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Gravity settling requires large tanks and extended residence times (often 24&ndash;48 hours)</li>
    <li>Settling removes only heavier particles; fine sludge and emulsified water remain</li>
    <li>Bag filters clog rapidly, requiring constant replacement and labor</li>
    <li>Filtration alone cannot remove dissolved or emulsified water</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Centrifugal Separation</h3>

  <p>
    A disc stack centrifuge overcomes every limitation of conventional settling and filtration. By generating centrifugal forces of <strong>7,000 Gs or higher</strong>, the centrifuge compresses hours of gravity settling into seconds of continuous processing. It simultaneously separates solids, free water, and emulsified water in a single pass.
  </p>

