  <!-- ── Centrifuge Operation ── -->
  <h2 id="centrifuge-operation">Used Oil Centrifuge Operation</h2>

  <p>
    A self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge processes used oil in a continuous flow-through mode. The oil enters the rotating bowl through a stationary inlet and is distributed across a stack of conical discs. These discs create thin layers of oil, dramatically shortening the distance that contaminant particles must travel to be separated.
  </p>

  <p>
    At rotational speeds generating over <strong>7,000 Gs</strong> of centrifugal force, the centrifuge separates particles as small as <strong>0.5 microns</strong> and removes <strong>all free water</strong> from the used oil. The three phases discharge simultaneously:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clean Oil (Light Phase):</strong> Exits through the top disc stack outlet under pressure</li>
    <li><strong>Water (Heavy Phase):</strong> Discharges continuously through a separate gravity-disc outlet</li>
    <li><strong>Sludge (Solids):</strong> Accumulates in the bowl periphery and is periodically ejected through automatic self-cleaning discharge ports</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The self-cleaning cycle is PLC-controlled, ejecting accumulated sludge at timed intervals without interrupting oil flow. This enables 24/7 continuous operation with minimal operator intervention.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Separation Efficiency ── -->
  <h2 id="separation-efficiency">Separation Efficiency</h2>

  <p>
    The separation performance of a used oil centrifuge is measured across several key parameters:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Particle Removal:</strong> Sub-micron solid separation down to 0.5&mu; at rated temperature. Metal fines, carbon particles, and dirt are continuously removed.</li>
    <li><strong>Water Removal:</strong> All free water is separated and discharged through the heavy-phase outlet. Typical residual moisture in the clean oil is below 0.5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Ash Reduction:</strong> Ash content (metallic additives and combustion byproducts) is reduced by 80&ndash;95% in a single pass through the centrifuge.</li>
    <li><strong>Emulsion Breaking:</strong> The high G-force generated by a disc stack centrifuge is sufficient to <a href="/waste-oil-emulsion-centrifuge/">break stable oil-water emulsions</a> that filters and gravity settling cannot address.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Processing temperature significantly affects efficiency. Operating at <strong>180&deg;F</strong> or higher reduces oil viscosity, enabling faster throughput and finer particle separation for a given centrifuge model.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Benefits ── -->
  <h2 id="benefits">Benefits of Used Oil Centrifuges</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Three-Phase Separation:</strong> Simultaneously removes solids, free water, and emulsified water in a single pass &mdash; no multi-stage filtration required.</li>
    <li><strong>Small Footprint:</strong> A complete centrifuge system occupies a fraction of the floor space required by settling tanks and filter banks of equivalent capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Low Operating Cost:</strong> No filter media to purchase or dispose of. Mechanical separation eliminates consumable costs.</li>
    <li><strong>High Efficiency:</strong> Sub-micron particle removal and near-complete water separation exceed the capability of any filter-based system.</li>
    <li><strong>Emulsion Breaking:</strong> High centrifugal force breaks oil-water emulsions that are impossible to separate by gravity or filtration.</li>
    <li><strong>30+ Year Service Life:</strong> Industrial disc stack centrifuges are built with stainless steel bowls and hardened components designed for decades of continuous heavy-duty service.</li>
    <li><strong>Automatic Operation:</strong> PLC-controlled self-cleaning cycles and <a href="/industrial-centrifuge-controls/">integrated control panels</a> enable unattended operation.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Limitations ── -->
  <h2 id="limitations">Limitations</h2>

  <p>
    While centrifuges offer superior separation performance, there are practical considerations to weigh:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Capital Cost:</strong> Industrial disc stack centrifuge systems have a higher upfront cost than settling tanks or filter presses. However, the lower operating cost typically delivers payback within months at commercial processing volumes.</li>
    <li><strong>Utility Requirements:</strong> Centrifuges require three-phase electrical power and a clean water supply for bowl flushing and sealing during operation.</li>
    <li><strong>Noise:</strong> High-speed rotating equipment generates operational noise. Proper installation with vibration isolation and, where needed, acoustic enclosures addresses this concern.</li>
    <li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Periodic inspection of seals, bearings, and disc stacks is required. Scheduled maintenance intervals are typically every 4,000&ndash;8,000 operating hours, depending on the severity of the application.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Design Considerations ── -->
  <h2 id="design-considerations">Design Considerations for Used Oil Centrifuges</h2>

  <p>
    Used oil presents specific engineering challenges that must be addressed during centrifuge system design:
  </p>

  <h3>Acidic Feedstock</h3>

  <p>
    Used engine oil is often acidic due to combustion byproducts (sulfuric and nitric acid precursors). The centrifuge bowl and all wetted parts must be constructed from corrosion-resistant alloys &mdash; typically <strong>316L stainless steel</strong> &mdash; and sealing elastomers must be chemically compatible with acidic oil.
  </p>

  <h3>Chemical Injection</h3>

  <p>
    In some applications, demulsifying chemicals or pH-adjusting agents are injected upstream of the centrifuge to improve separation. The system design must include metering pumps and injection quills with adequate mixing length before the centrifuge inlet.
  </p>

  <h3>Water Phase Proportion</h3>

  <p>
    Used oil from different sources contains widely varying water content. Oil from engine drain collectors may contain 5&ndash;10% water, while refinery slop oil can exceed 40%. The centrifuge gravity disc (water outlet) must be sized to match the expected water-to-oil ratio. Improperly sized gravity discs cause oil loss through the water outlet or water carryover into the clean oil.
  </p>

  <h3>Special Elastomers</h3>

  <p>
    Standard nitrile (NBR) seals may swell or degrade in contact with certain used oil chemistries. Viton (FKM) or EPDM elastomers are specified depending on the specific contaminant profile of the feedstock.
  </p>

